g\\nColleges\\nFacilities\\nEvents and Attractions\\nFinance\\nLabor and Agents\\nLeagues\\nOlympics\\nOpinion\\nPeople and Pop Culture\\nSports and Society\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nMedia\\nTech\\nExecutive Transactions\\nMarketing\\n\\nAll Topics\\n\\n\\nInternational\\nData\\nFranchises\\nEsports\\nBetting\\nColleges\\nFacilities\\nEvents and Attractions\\nFinance\\nLabor and Agents\\nLeagues\\nOlympics\\nOpinion\\nPeople and Pop Culture\\nSports and Society\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nPrint\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nDaily Editions\\n\\n\\nLatest Issue\\nMorning Buzz\\nClosing Bell\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n|\\n\\n\\nNewsletters\\n\\n\\nView All\\nBetting\\nCollege\\nFootball\\nGaming\\nMarketing\\nMedia\\nPower Up\\nTech\\nUnpacks\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n|\\n\\n\\nWeekly Issue\\n7.15.2024\\n\\n\\nDigital Edition\\n7.01.2024\\n6.24.2024\\n6.17.2024\\n6.10.2024\\n6.03.2024\\n5.27.2024\\n5.20.2024\\n5.13.2024\\n5.06.2024\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nTech\\nNCAA approves Liberty League to use in-game play calling technology from GoRout\\nLiberty League's seven teams will institute GoRout\\u2019s game system, GoRout Gridiron, across in-conference football games during the 2024-25 season.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nBy Rob Schaefer\\n7.16.2024\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nGoRout/Liberty League\\nAfter approving in-helmet radio devices for football competitions this spring, the NCAA\\u2019s experimentation with various methods of coach-to-player communication is expanding at the Division III level.\\n\\nThe Liberty League recently had a proposal of experimental use for in-game play calling technology provided by GoRout approved by the NCAA \\u2013 and will now have its seven teams institute GoRout\\u2019s game system, GoRout Gridiron, across in-conference football games (and out-of-conference matchups if their opponent consents) during the 2024-25 season.\\n\\nThis pilot will mark GoRout\\u2019s first go-around in live football competition, although its diamond sports product is used by more than 400 college baseball/softball teams and practice-focused football system, GoRout Scout, by multiple NFL clubs and big-name college programs including Alabama, Auburn and Rutgers.\\n\\nHere is how it works: from the sideline, coaches dictate play calls from a tablet, which beams instruction to wearable devices on athletes\\u2019 wrist or waistbands. GoRout Scout conveys those play calls through diagrams, while Gridiron displays simple text.\\n\\n\\u201cOur technology allows coaches \\u2013 during halftime, during periods after they go through a possession \\u2013 to make updates and adjustments to the text that\\u2019s being called and sent in,\\u201d GoRout CEO\\u00a0Mike Rolih told SBJ in a recent interview. \\u201c[Text is] not static, whereas an image is very difficult at that point to dry to redraw.\\u201d\\n\\nThat communication is encrypted, ensuring security in the cloud, and transmitted over 5G with an assist from Kore Wireless, GoRout\\u2019s networking partner. The wearables themselves can be flipped off at any time via the coach\\u2019s control panel and are layered with protective padding, ensuring security on the field.\\n\\n\\u201cWe spend a tremendous amount of time talking about security,\\u201d\\u00a0Rolih said. \\u201cA player would literally have to want to give the opponent to the opportunity to see the call [for signs to be stolen].\\u201d\\n\\n   1/2    Photo: GoRout    2/2    Photo: GoRout PREVIOUS NEXT\\nGoRout will provide each of the Liberty League\\u2019s schools with 10 wearable devices, two tablets and 24/7 technical support. That package\\u2019s pricing could range between $5,000 to $10,000 per year, GoRout chief partnerships officer Drew Robinson told SBJ.\\n\\n\\u201cThat\\u2019s a fairly wide window, but when you compare that to what we\\u2019ve heard some of the FBS teams are spending \\u2013 upwards of $100,000 \\u2013 on the helmet technologies and the audio technologies, this is going to be an attainable price point,\\u201d Robinson said, adding that GoRout\\u2019s system carries less liability consideration as altering game helmets as well.\\n\\nThat accessibility and visual dynamic is what separates GoRout from verbal communication methods.\\n\\n\\u201cThe kids that are coming up to play right now, and the coaches that are getting into coaching, most of them don\\u2019t communicate the way we used to communicate when we were growing up. They\\u2019ve never lived without a device in their hand,\\u201d Rolith said. \\u201cThis is a very natural communication methodology for them.\\u201d\\n\\nThe NCAA waiver allows three players on each team to wear a GoRout device per offensive or defensive snap, with no limit assigned for special teams plays. There also will not be a signal cutoff, such as in the NFL\\u2019s use of helmet radios, when communication is stymied with 15 seconds left on the play clock.\\n\\nGoRout will survey Liberty League coaches and athletes throughout the season to garner feedback on the technology to better understand how its system is being used and to inform product enhancements. \\u201cAll of our GoRout products are truly being built for coaches by coaches,\\u201d said Robinson, who served as a student assistant on Syracuse\\u2019s football coaching staff in the mid-2000\\u2019s and has worked in Rutgers, Syracuse and Western Michigan\\u2019s athletic departments.\\n\\nIn that vein, Liberty League commissioner Tracy King credited Union College coach Jon Drach, a member of the NCAA Football Rules Committee and GoRout Scout user during his time at Wilkes University, as catalyzing the relationship between the conference and vendor.\\n\\n\\u201cThe use of technology in sports, especially wearable technology is something that\\u2019s rapidly evolving,\\u201d King said. \\u201cWe felt this was an opportunity for us to be on the forefront of Division III.\\u201d\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nPREVIOUS\\nReturn Home\\n\\n\\nNEXT\\nReturn Home\\n\